{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/head-lice/background-information/prevalence-risk-factors/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"e21d9025-2ac4-59c8-a69f-297f822ddce3","slug":"prevalence-risk-factors","fullItemName":"Prevalence and risk factors","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 6a03a4cc-ade2-41a9-a7a5-12bf3744fad8 --><h2>How common is head lice infestation and what are the predisposing factors?</h2><!-- end field 6a03a4cc-ade2-41a9-a7a5-12bf3744fad8 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 481d0184-1fff-4601-bc02-4c44aac22d54 --><!-- begin field 3caa8193-83ea-4f5e-85c2-790bf6a7e314 --><ul><li><strong>There is little information on the current prevalence of head lice infestation in the UK: </strong><ul><li>In a survey of 31 primary schools in Wales (n = 2793), live head lice were detected in 8.3% of children who were screened (95% CI 7.3 to 9.4) [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/head-lice/references/\">Thomas et al, 2006</a>].</li><li>In a survey of 14 English schools in Exmouth, Loughborough, Leeds, and South Shields, the proportion of pupils infested with head lice ranged from 4-22% [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/head-lice/references/\">Downs et al, 2002</a>].</li><li>In one randomized controlled trial, 4,037 Welsh children were screened for head lice, and a prevalence of 4.1% was found [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/head-lice/references/\">Roberts et al, 2000</a>].</li></ul></li><li>Head lice infestation can affect anyone of any age. However, it is most common in children aged 4-11 years (the peak age for infestation is 7-8 years), and is more common in girls than boys [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/head-lice/references/\">PHMEG, 2012</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/head-lice/references/\">BAD, 2014</a>].</li><li>A cross-sectional Belgian study (n = 6169) aimed to determine the prevalence of head lice in school children ;and to investigate the independent association between individual characteristics of the child, socio-economic status of the family, and head lice [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/head-lice/references/\">Willems et al, 2005</a>]:<ul><li>The evidence suggested that head lice are significantly more common in:<ul><li>Children with long hair — this increases the difficulty of treatment and may be a reason for the raised prevalence in girls, who are more likely than boys to wear their hair long.</li><li>Children with more siblings — because more resources are needed to check for (and treat) head lice.</li><li>Families of lower socio-economic status — as families are expected to purchase treatments in Belgium, those of lower socio-economic status are disadvantaged.</li></ul></li><li>However, the authors concluded that the prevalence of head lice is determined by clustering of children (for example in large families or a class at school) rather than by characteristics of the child (such as hair length or socio-economic status).</li></ul></li><li>There is no evidence that head lice have a preference for either clean or dirty hair [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/head-lice/references/\">PHMEG, 2012</a>].</li></ul><!-- end field 3caa8193-83ea-4f5e-85c2-790bf6a7e314 --><!-- end item 481d0184-1fff-4601-bc02-4c44aac22d54 -->","topic":{"id":"ca628e0c-ce13-5d42-b253-54a69b51d894","topicId":"e347bf30-a684-4ab6-843a-e2d2929ff4ca","topicName":"Head lice","slug":"head-lice","lastRevised":"Last revised in December 2016","chapters":[{"id":"c07f1a11-a6fc-5dc9-b489-c79c00eed1b2","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"1c07399f-6032-532b-aab2-6e7a99c32991","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subC